    <h2>the project</h2>
    The purpose of the Artemis Project '98 is to give a group of talented young women from Providence the opportunity to explore computers.  We believe that young women can benefit from a program geared towards access to technology and discussion of issues relevant to their lives.
    
    <h2>history</h2>
    The Artemis Project was the created by two Brown students, Laurie Kardos and Jesse Marmon, in <a href="../artemis_96/home.html">1996</a> and was strengthened and expanded by <a href="http://www.cs.brown.edu/people/st/homepage/index.html">Saori Taichi</a> and Jess Howell in <a href="../artemis_97/home.html">1997</a>.
    
    <h2>coordinators</h2>
    We, <a href="leaders/mi/home.html">Miecha Bryant</a> and <a href="leaders/rk/home.html">Rupali Kotwal</a>, are Brown University undergrads.  We have an interest in technology and building relationships between the Providence community and Brown.
    
    <h2>participants</h2>
    All of the participants in the Artemis Project '98 have completed eighth grade and will enter Providence high schools in the fall.  The girls arrive on July 6, so keep an eye out for the homepages they build this summer.
